ofile?gid=saruu@thesaryrntavern>Saruu</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:pink;'>Tavern Floor Sweeper</span></span><br>  Posts: 39<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(4/29/03 12:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntaverncommonsroom.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5113.topic&index=41>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Garbhad, you should know better.</span><hr size=1> Garbhad, please, please don't ever try to back up an argument with information you've gotten from a television commercial.<br>
<br>
That commercial you quote has totally useless information.  Basically, the commercial says that of all the people pulled over for reckless driving AND who exhibit signs of intoxication sufficient for the officer to test them, one third of THOSE people test positive for pot.  So we aren't talking about reckless drivers in general, we are only talking about drivers the cops believe are under the influence of something.  But what percentage of all reckless drivers do those drivers represent?  60%?  3%?  They don't tell us.  So you can draw no hard conclusions about reckless drivers.  Useless.  <br>
<br>
It would be much more helpful for the commercial to tell us what fraction of ALL reckless drivers test positive for pot.  Until we know that, we don't know who is more dangerous to us on the road--pot smokers or coffee drinkers, cell phone users, the guy changing the CD, the chick putting on her lipstick, etc.  Now, why doesn't the commercial use a more useful statistic that would stand up to logical scrutiny?  Perhaps they are hoping most people will miss the &quot;of those tested&quot; part or, if it is caught, it will be misunderstood.  Apparently, that's working.  This is a perfect example of inflammatory, distorted statistics quoted to elicit a specific response.  <br>
<br>
However, that backfires if you are paying attention.  Since the DOT (or whomever) uses the statistic they do, you can infer that the percentage of reckless drivers testing positive for pot must be a hell of a lot smaller than all of the other dangerous drivers.  After all, if the DOT did have a useful statistic showing a significant percentage of reckless drivers were pot smokers, they would certainly use it.  But they don't.  Therefore, the statistic must not exist.<br>
<br>
I don't smoke pot, I don't think it should be legalized and I certainly think only stupid people smoke up then go driving around endangering others.  But this series of anti-drug commercials that have been around lately are so misleading and logically tilted, they are doing more harm than good.  (Especially that idiotic &quot;smoking pot makes you pregnant&quot; one--I'd love to see a comparison of conceptions under the influence of pot vs. under the influence of cheap beer.  Hooza!)<br>
<br>
Durn spelling... <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=saruu@thesaryrntavern>Saruu</A> at: 4/29/03 1:05:21 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=cogmatix>Cogmatix</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:red;'>President<br>of the<br>Knightrider<br>Fanclub</span></span><br>  Posts: 1040<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(4/29/03 1:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntaverncommonsroom.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5113.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> F!</span><hr size=1> That &quot;statistic&quot; also highlights a major problem in determining whether or not someone is actually high or has just smoked pot in the last week or so. It's pretty much impossible to do, unless you want to just label everyone with red or lazy eyes as stoned people.<br>
<br>
It's not like aclohol, you can't just test someone and say &quot;Aha! You're high RIGHT NOW!&quot;. Unless you quantify that they are actually impaired in any way whatsoever (ie, falling over a lot like drunk people are prone to do) all that statiic proves is that there really are a lot of people that smoke pot.<br>
<br>
Maybe we should just build more jails or something, it's certainly easier than researching a better way to deal with it.<br>
<br>
Cog<br>
